  "text": "Pack a tiny suitcase-it's time to move! You don't fly at night-except during migration. Migration is when you and your friends fly to somewhere warmer for a few months to avoid a cold winter. You may migrate hundreds or even thousands of miles. You usually migrate in late summer or early fall. Before migrating. you need to eat a lot to increase your body weight. Your body stores a layer of fat to help you survive the long journey. Most hummingbirds in Canada and the United States migrate south to Mexico or Central America. Some South American species migrate north to these areas. too. the hummingbird is the smallest migratory bird in the world. the rufous tuznmingbird migrates the longest distance. You migrate by yourself. not in a flock. as other birds do. Even young hummingbirds go it alone when migrating for the first time You'll probably use the same migration route every year of your life. Not all hummingbirds migrate. If it doesn't get very cold where you live. you can stay put for the winter. Central America there yet? Time to stop for a snack! O",
